o adapted and developed to accommodate this global activism. Provocative and eye-opening, #iranelection reveals the new online ecology of social protest and offers a prehistory, of sorts, of the uses of hashtags and trending topics, selfies and avatar activism, and citizen journalism and YouTube mashups.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCitizen journalismzIran. 0aInternet and activismzIran. 0aPresidentszIranxElectiony2009. 0aSocial mediaxPolitical aspectszIran. 4aFacebook. 4aGoogle. 4aInstagram. 4aIranian Election Crisis 2009. 4aIranian Women's movements. 4aMeme. 4aSelfie. 4aTwitter. 4aYouTube. 4acitizen journalism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479673640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804796736423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804796736.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles